    <text>
        <body>
            
            <div1 type="letter">
                
                <pb facs="nei.j4a.12.25-26_0001" />
                
                <note type="curatorial">46 House Collection</note>
                <fw type="curatorial">25</fw>
                
                <fw type="letterhead">
                    <hi rend="caps">THE UNIVERSITY OF TEXAS
                        <lb/>
                    AUSTIN, TEXAS
                        <lb/>
                
                    DEPARTMENT OF ENGLISH</hi>
                </fw>   
                
                <opener>
                    <dateline>April 9, 1926</dateline>
                
                    <salute>Dear Mr. Neihardt:</salute>
                </opener> 
                <p>I have received the autographed copies of <hi rend="underline">The Song of the Indian Wars</hi> and <hi rend="underline">Poetic Values</hi>, and I wish to thank you heartily for your trouble in this matter. I shall take occasion to display one of these volumes to my pupils when I come to speak of your work in my classes during the coming summer.</p>
                
                <p>The Macmillan Company has graciously granted me free permission to include your "When I am Dead" in my <hi rend="underline">Selections</hi> from Later <hi rend="underline">American Writers</hi>. When I made this <add>single</add> selection I had not read deeply into your work. Since I have read all your longer poems and also looked into House's book on your life and work, I have suddenly come to realize that one poem is inadequate, even in my condensed anthology for high-school use. I therefore wish to ask you to allow me to add "Battle-Cry" as a second selection. On the basis of the hope that you will allow this poem also, I have revised my introductory note, a copy of which I am enclosing to you. I wish you would look over my note and make any suggestions for improvements or corrections that occur to you. I want to make my notes both helpful and
                
                    <pb facs="nei.j4a.12.25-26_0002"/>
                    <fw type="curatorial">26</fw>
                
                    accurate and I find that the safest plan is to appeal to the authors themselves when there is opportunity to do so.</p>
                
                <p>I am impressed with the adaptability of your narrative poems for classroom use, and it may be that I can adopt your school edition of the first two poems in your epic cycle (the Modern Reader's Series) in my class at the Peabody College during the coming summer. This class will make intensive studies in recent American literature, and I presume most of the members of this class will be teachers of English. I have not as yet made out the list of <unclear>texts</unclear>, but I rather think now that I shall include your two poems as an example of recent narrative or epic poetry dealing with American themes.</p>
                
                <p>My broader acquaintance with your work has given me much pleasure. You may like to know that when <hi rend="underline">The Song of the Indian Wars</hi> came a few days ago, I began in the afternoon to read and I could not put the book down until I had finished it. I congratulate you on opening up a new field in American literature and I am delighted with the successful way in which you are handling this fresh material. Texas has a similar field to be exploited by someone.</p>
                <closer>
                    <salute>Very sincerely and gratefully yours,</salute>
                    
                    <signed>L.W. Payne, Jr.</signed>
                
                    
                    <address>
                        <addrLine>Mr. John <hi rend="caps">G.</hi> Neihardt</addrLine>
                        <addrLine>Branson, Missouri</addrLine>
                    </address>
                </closer>
                
            </div1>
